GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 1178
Short Title: The NC Teacher Pay Competitiveness Act. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Rubin, Prather, R. Pierce, and F. Jackson (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
May 4, 2026
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO INCREASE TEACHER COMPENSATION AND ESTABLISH A PHASED
3 FRAMEWORK FOR CONTINUED COMPENSATION INCREASES FOR TEACHERS
4 OVER TIME IN ORDER TO COMPETE WITH PEER STATES IN THE
5 SOUTHEASTERN UNITED STATES AND TO REVISE ELIGIBILITY
6 REQUIREMENTS AND REDUCE FUNDS FOR THE OPPORTUNITY SCHOLARSHIP
7 PROGRAM.
8 Whereas, the North Carolina General Assembly has demonstrated a dangerous
9 inability to enact a comprehensive biennial State budget prior to the start of the fiscal year; and
10 Whereas, operating under the budget continuation statute due to legislative gridlock
11 leaves critical investments in our public workforce frozen, including stagnant and unfunded
12 salaries for public school educators; and
13 Whereas, in contrast, funding for private school vouchers through the Opportunity
14 Scholarship program has been statutorily codified to expand automatically, fully insulating
15 private school subsidies from the very budget impasses that freeze funding for public schools;
16 and
17 Whereas, the unchecked, automatic diversion of increasingly vast sums of public
18 taxpayer dollars to private institutions threatens the State's ability to fulfill its constitutional
19 obligation to provide every child with a sound, basic education; and
20 Whereas, average public school teacher compensation in North Carolina currently
21 lags behind every bordering state, severely undermining this State's ability to recruit and retain
22 highly qualified educators; and
23 Whereas, it is the intent of the General Assembly to demonstrate to the teachers of
24 this State that it will invest in their long-term growth in this State, as they serve the vast majority
25 of students in North Carolina; and
26 Whereas, this act will establish a phased, legally protected escalation of funding
27 designed to ensure that North Carolina, at minimum, continues to stay competitive in the
28 southeastern United States, as defined by the Department of Public Instruction, for teacher pay
29 through at least the 2032-2033 school year; Now, therefore,
30 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
31
32 PART I. PERMANENT TEACHER RAISES
33 SECTION 1.(a) Article 20 of Chapter 115C of the General Statutes is amended by
34 adding the following new sections to read:
